> Dear Sir,
>
>
> To fly a 5-inch FPV drone on a university campus in India, we must follow
> the rules under the Directorate General of Civil Aviation (DGCA) Drone
> Rules 2021. Even if we fly line-of-sight and below 20 m, permissions may
> still be required depending on the drone category and airspace zone.
>
> Below is the practical list of permissions we may need.
>
> 1. *DGCA / Digital Sky registration (mandatory)*
>
> We must register our drone on the Digital Sky Platform and obtain a UIN
> (Unique Identification Number) unless it is a nano drone.
>
> Drones must follow NPNT =E2=80=93 No Permission No Takeoff.
>
> Permission is requested through Digital Sky before each flight.
>
> 2. *Remote Pilot Certificate (sometimes required)*
>
> If our drone is more than 250 g (micro or above), the pilot must have a
> Remote Pilot Certificate from a DGCA-authorized training organization.
>
> A typical 5-inch FPV drone usually weighs 400=E2=80=93800 g, so it normal=
ly falls
> under Micro category.
>
> 3. *Airspace permission (depends on zone)*
>
> India divides airspace into zones:
>
> Green Zone =E2=86=92 No permission required (below ~120 m)
>
> Yellow Zone =E2=86=92 Permission from Air Traffic Control via Digital Sky
>
> Red Zone =E2=86=92 Permission from Ministry of Civil Aviation and other a=
gencies
>
> 4. *Local authority permission (very important)*
>
> Even if DGCA allows it, we still need:
>
> Written permission from the university administration
>
> Local police station / district administration if flying in public areas
>
> This is because drones cannot be flown over crowds or sensitive locations
> without approval.
>
> 5. *Safety Plans*
>
> Our plan (good practice)
>
>
> This is for your information.
>
>
> Regards
>
> Anil Nigam
